In LaTeX, you can generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically using the `table of contents` facility, which is handled by the `toc` file and controlled by the `toc` package (actually, it's a standard LaTeX mechanism, so no extra package is needed, but I'll mention the key component). Here's an example:

```latex
% ... earlier document content ...
\documentclass{book}  % or report, article (adjust to your document style)
\begin{document}

% To include the TOC mechanism
\tableofcontents
\addtocontents{toc}{\vspace{2pt}}  % optional: add some space above TOC

% Sectioning commands that will appear in the TOC
\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Background}
\subsection{Importance of the topic}
\section{Research Objectives}
\chapter{Literature Review}
\section{Theoretical Foundations}
\subsection{Related Work}

% ... rest of your document ...

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is used to include the automatically generated TOC in your document. LaTeX will take care of reading all sectioning commands (like `\chapter`, `\section`, `\subsection`, etc.) and creating the TOC entries.

**Important:** Make sure to have at least two         (empty lines) before `\tableofcontents` to distinguish it from previous content.

When you compile your document (e.g., with `pdflatex` or `xelatex`), the TOC will be generated and appear in your output PDF file.

Note: If you want more control over the TOC, you can use packages like `tocloft` or `hyperref` (for hyperlinks in the TOC) with additional configuration options.

To draw a chessboard from a FEN notation in LaTeX, we'll use the `xskak` package, which is a frontend to the `skak` chess library. Although `xskak` is specifically designed for LaTeX, I'll provide the essentials, as the syntax is minimalism-friendly. (Note: Install the `xskak` package if you haven't already: `texliveonweb` has it, or add `xskak` to your `tex` system's package manager.)

Here's the LATEX code to display a chessboard from a FEN notation:
```latex
\documentclass[a4paper,10pt]{article}
\usepackage[with_17th_char]{xskak}
\newchesssetup{showall = 1} % 1 for detailed board, 0 for compact

\begin{document}

\noindent\chessboard{
  r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK1NR
}

\end{document}
```
Let me explain the key parts:

* We include the `xskak` package with the `with_17th_char` option, which allows us to use the 17-character FEN rank (for better board alignment).
* We set `showall = 1` in `\newchesssetup` to display the board with ranks and files (you can set it to 0 for a compact board without them).
* The `\chessboard` command takes the FEN string as an argument, which represents the initial position of the chessboard.

In this example, the FEN string `r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK1NR` specifies the starting position (before any moves). This code will render the corresponding chessboard.

Compile this code with `pdflatex` or your preferred LaTeX compiler to obtain the PDF output with the chessboard.

Remember to adjust the FEN string to visualize any desired board position. Happy typesetting!

